post.author: bpanjavan
post.title: ASP.NET - Inline code on ASPX Page
post.content:
I knew you could do this but my colleague had to remind me on the exact syntax the other day so I told myself I had better blog about this before I forget again.

I arrived onto the scene of professional web development after the .NET page and code-behind model became the norm.  So it was my surprise that you could put inline code on the ASPX markup page.  I thought the only exception was for data-binding but apparently you could do it anywhere.

Below I'm adding the code using proper syntax on the markup page to do so.


The method itself outputs a string that will be placed on the page.  Notice that I use the protected modifier which allows the markup page to see the method.

The resulting output:


Q: Does it always have to be a string?
A: No.  With .NET boxing/un-boxing, any variable/object that has the ToString() method (which is ALL objects in .NET) can be used.  If you don't output a string, then whatever the output of the ToString() method of the object will be used.  Here's an example of a call to return a Customer object:


The code returns a customer object.  I've overridden the ToString() method.


The resulting output.  Notice the output is what I've defined in the ToString() method.  I did not HAVE to overwrite the ToString() method.  If I had not, then the default ToString() would have been output instead.
